        "headline":"Flyers flail in Detroit while Penguins eke out victory against Lightning",
        "body":"<p>Henrik Zetterberg had two goals and an assist to lead the <strong>Detroit Red Wings</strong> to a 5-2 win over the <strong>Philadelphia Flyers</strong> on Saturday. Pavel Datsyuk and Niklas Kronwall each added a goal and two assists for the hosts.</p><p>Among other games, the Colorado Avalanche extended its winning start to the season to five games by beating the Washington Capitols; the San Jose Sharks' Tomas Hertl netted his seventh goal of the season but left the game with an injury as the Sharks edged the Ottawa Senators, and the Pittsburgh Penguins came up with a winner with 19 seconds left to edge a nine-goal clinker against the Tampa Bay Lightning.</p><p>Detroit also got a goal from Todd Bertuzzi, and had three power-play goals after failing on its first 10 opportunities this season. Daniel Alfredsson had three assists, and Jimmy Howard made 32 saves. Erik Gustafsson and Tye McGinn scored for Philadelphia, who dropped to 1-2 under interim coach Craig Berube, who replaced the fired Peter Laviolette on Monday.</p><p>Alex Tanguay scored twice as the <strong>Colorado Avalanche</strong> beat the <strong>Washington Capitals</strong> 5-1. Semyon Varlamov made 40 saves against his old side as Colorado made it 5-0 for the first time since 1994-95 when the team was based in Quebec. Rookie Nathan MacKinnon added his first NHL goal and an assist, and Matt Duchene and Jamie McGinn also scored for Colorado. Washington has lost three straight.</p><p>The <strong>San Jose Sharks</strong> rookie Tomas Hertl improved his league-leading goal tally as the Sharks downed the <strong>Ottawa Senators</strong> 3-2. Hertl later had to be helped to the dressing room after taking a hard hit from Clarke MacArthur late in the second period and did not return. The Sharks announced he was under observation.</p><p>Brent Burns got the tiebreaker in the third period and Patrick Marleau also secored for the Sharks, who were finally fighting in a tight game after outscoring the opposition by 16 goals in the first four games. Zach Smith and Bobby Ryan scored for the Senators, who have lost three straight.</p><p>Sidney Crosby had three goals and an assist while Matt Niskanen scored the tiebreaking goal with 18.6 seconds left, lifting the <strong>Pittsburgh Penguins</strong> past the <strong>Tampa Bay Lightning</strong> 5-4.</p><p>Niskanen scored the winning goal from the top of the left circle, with an assist from Crosby.</p><p>Crosby had tied it 3-3 just 25 seconds into the third, and then put Pittsburgh in front when he scored from the right circle with 9:34 remaining. Crosby has a point in all five games this season. It is his longest streak to start a season since a six-game stretch in October 2005.</p><p>Alex Killorn tied the game 4-4 for the Lightning with 3:02 remaining. Valtteri Filppula, Steven Stamkos and Teddy Purcell also scored for Tampa Bay. </p><p>Goalie Carey Price made 39 saves to help the<strong> Montreal Canadiens</strong> defeat the<strong> Vancouver Canucks</strong> 4-1.</p><p>Lars Eller got credit for a bizarre short-handed winner. Canucks defensemen Dan Hamhuis and Jason Garrison got tangled up behind the Vancouver net on a breakout, with the puck rebounding into the crease and off both the goalie's skates before dribbling over the line.</p><p>Eller, who wasn't even in the Canucks' zone at the time of the goal, was the last Canadiens player to touch the puck.</p><p>Max Pacioretty, Tomas Plekanec and Josh Gorges also scored for Montreal, while Henrik Sedin netted for Vancouver.</p><p>Loui Eriksson scored from a hard angle in the opening minute of the third period for his first goal for the <strong>Boston Bruins</strong>, which topped the <strong>Columbus Blue Jackets</strong> 3-1.</p><p>Playing their first road game, the Bruins also got a goal from Chris Kelly, and an empty-net tally from Milan Lucic while Jack Johnson scored for the Blue Jackets.</p><p><strong>St Louis Blues</strong>' David Backes scored twice as the unbeaten Blues topped the slumping <strong>New York Rangers</strong> 5-3.</p><p>The Blues, who haven't trailed at all this season, are 4-0 for the first time in franchise history. New York, which has four games left on a season-opening, nine-game trip, has lost three in a row by a combined score of 20-5.</p><p><strong>Chicago Blackhawks</strong>' Corey Crawford made 28 saves to preserve their 2-1 lead over the winless <strong>Buffalo Sabres</strong>. Buffalo (0-5-1) has been outscored 16-6 in its worst start since the 1999-2000 season.</p><p>Seth Jones scored his first NHL goal, helping the <strong>Nashville Predators </strong>edge the <strong>New York Islanders</strong> 3-2.</p><p><strong>Minnesota Wild</strong> rookies Justin Fontaine and Mathew Dumba both scored their first NHL goals in a 5-1 win over the <strong>Dallas Stars</strong>.</p><p><strong>Toronto Maple Leaf</strong> Dave Bolland scored the winning goal 2:09 into overtime against the <strong>Edmonton Oilers</strong>, after Joffrey Lupul tied it with 31 seconds left in regulation in a 6-5 win against Edmonton.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419831051|2013-10-17T10:28:06Z|b03720840c7a8664223406c6cacfde816cbcf6b9 -->",
