        "body":"<p>Three games into the new season and the NHL saw its first managerial casualty. What is it that Peter Laviolette did wrong at the Philadelphia Flyers? If he knew on Monday, Flyers general manager Paul Holmgren didn't seem to offer many specifics. </p><p>\"I've had concerns for a while, and you kind of hope things are going to turn around and I didn't feel like we were in a position to hope any longer,\" Holmgren said, as he announced the team had fired Laviolette as head coach after only three regular-season games.</p><p>But why? For Flyers chairman Ed Snider it started at training camp, which was apparently \"one of the worst … I had ever seen\", where \"nobody shined\" and he \"couldn't point to one thing as a positive\". </p><p>It would stand to reason that the turning point had to have happened sometime between this week and the end of last season, which the Flyers finished out of the playoffs, when Snider said Laviolette had been \"a very good coach for us. A good coach in this league. We're thrilled to have him.\" </p><p>For Holmgren, the decision to dump Laviolette was based on a \"gut feeling\". As for the regular-season start, he said (accurately) that \"0-3 is 0-3\". There is still a long way to go, he said: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>…but it was more about how we played. It was unacceptable. We don't look like a team at all.</p></blockquote><p>That definition might be up for debate, but certainly the Flyers of 2013 haven't looked like one team in particular: the Flyers of 2010, the team that ended up <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xdVn42-vOt8\">one strange Patrick Kane goal away from a Stanley Cup</a>. </p><p>Back then, the Flyers appeared a force to be reckoned with. On their way to the Final, they became one of only a lucky (skilled?) few teams in the history of the league to overcome a three-game deficit to win a series – the others being the 1942 Toronto Maple Leafs and the 1975 New York Islanders. Philadelphia beat back the Boston Bruins to take the first round 4-3. The win put them in the conference finals for the second time in three seasons. After the loss in the Final to the Chicago Blackhawks the team re-tooled, and by the spring of 2012 they finally looked like a serious contender to the formidable Pittsburgh Penguins, topping them in a wild first-round series. </p><p>Then came the injuries, bedeviling the team through 2013's shortened season and leading to an early summer. Why the organization didn't ditch Laviolette then remains as mysterious as those words from Snider from months ago, about Laviolette being a good coach. Perhaps we must simply assume those words were genuine. What else can we do? How else does this make sense? What else can we do but assume Snider, at least, made his decision on Laviolette only after seeing training camp and the start to this new season? After seeing all the mistakes?</p><p>Though he is the first coach to be dismissed this campaign, Laviolette is at least sharing the headlines. In the first week of this young NHL season, we've already had at least two fiery confrontation over or through the dividing glass between the benches. The first was between new Colorado Avalanche coach Patrick Roy and Anaheim Ducks head coach Bruce Boudreau. </p><p><strong><a href=\"http://youtu.be/FxW_n8keVPg\">Reading on mobile? Watch this video here</a></strong></p><p>The second came on Saturday night in Vancouver. The new man steering the Canucks, John Tortorella, <a href=\"http://media.tumblr.com/0c4ba021f8cceaefc7835c4997d9b453/tumblr_inline_mu9n5j7EMI1rq0awt.gif\">got into a shouting match</a> with, seemingly, pretty much everyone on the Edmonton Oilers' coaching staff – most notably with <a href=\"http://imgur.com/vXCFnh1\">assistant coach Keith Acton</a>. Neither was much impressed with the other. </p><p>To listen to Don Cherry explain it all is to hear that these coaches (Roy specifically) are only keeping it alive back there on the bench. \"The players love this,\" Grapes said Saturday night, during his weekly sermon on the CBC and over a clip of Roy flipping out. \"They're in the game!\" </p><p>Well, perhaps. The Canucks won 6-2 after all. Maybe that's what coaching is – or at least part of it. If so, it's a part Laviolette filled during his time in Philly, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4LmW6Q9Wtg4\">even mixing it up once physically with the Dallas Stars' Steve Ott on the way to the dressing room</a> between periods (an incident which he seemed to immediately \"forget\"). And anyone who watched HBO's 24/7 knows Laviolette is no shrinking violet. He can be as enraged and excited as any of them.</p><p>Over at Puck Daddy, in asking the same main question (\"Why?\"), <a href=\"http://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/peter-laviolette-fired-flyers-taking-fall-bad-luck-142606410--nhl.html\">Greg Wyshynski reviews the management above Laviolette</a>. Specifically, he notes the lack of offseason acquisitions that might have given Laviolette more to work with on the ice (read: Shea Weber, Ryan Suter). The team, he writes, is a mess \"but its downward trajectory tracks back to one guy: The Chairman of the Board.\" That's Snider.</p><p>Perhaps it does. </p><p>Back in what could still be considered the (recent) glory days, just before the 2012 Winter Classic matchup with the New York Rangers, Laviolette pep-talked his team. \"We're going to make mistakes,\" he said. \"But stay loose and allow yourself to make mistakes, allow yourself to be great. But whatever you do, don't get all clammed up and caught up in the day.\"</p><p>On Monday, a reporter quizzed Snider about Laviolette's replacement, Craig Berube. The Flyers haven't won a championship in 38 years, the reporter reminded Snider, so why bring in a guy like Berube (who spent seven years of his professional career on the Flyers' bench), who is \"steeped in that sort of culture … a culture that hasn't won a championship in four decades.\" </p><p>Snider pointed out that the team has visited the finals a few times:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>That's the culture … the culture is to win. Thirty teams are trying to win the Cup and we're doing our damnedest to do it. That's our culture.</p></blockquote><p>He repeated it, interrupting the reporter, snapping: \"That's our culture.\" When it was suggested that the team might need a \"fresh perspective\", Snider simply said, \"No, we don't need a fresh perspective.\" Case closed. No room for error.</p><p>So, one final question: What makes a good coach? Or, more specifically, what is it that Ed Snider thinks makes someone a good coach? It's difficult to say, given the current situation. But we can ponder one thing. If Don Cherry is right about what a coach must do, maybe Snider could at least learn something from Roy or Tortorella about leading by example. And if it is the case that he could, then we might also wonder why Snider found he couldn't learn the same thing from the man he just fired.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419371932|2013-10-17T10:28:06Z|316fd57c1f0f518ace7d3104b68a0dac2d488f5f -->",
