        "trailText":"<p><strong>Colin Horgan:</strong> Ottawa Senator's Eric Gryba suspended for two games for hit on Montreal Canadiens' Lars Eller; Minnesota Wild's Josh Harding doesn't let multiple sclerosis stop him; Toronto Maple Leafs struggle against Boston Bruins</p>",
        "headline":"Eric Gryba hit on Lars Eller signals bloody start to NHL playoffs",
        "body":"<p>The NHL playoffs are now in full swing. We look at the main storylines from the first round of games:</p><h2>Lars Eller left bloodied, dazed and confused by Eric Gryba</h2><p>The good news first: As of Thursday evening, Montreal Canadiens forward Lars Eller is going to survive. The bad news? The reason we're even wondering about that in the first place: With about 6:30 left in the second period of Game One against Ottawa Thursday, Eller was totally flattened mid-ice by Ottawa's Eric Gryba. Here's the clip (warning: blood).</p><p><em></em></p><p>Gryba got a five-minute major for the hit, and though the Habs capitalized on it with a goal, they basically completely ran out of gas by a few minutes into the third and ended up losing 4-2. </p><p>Back to Eller. <a href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/opinion/stanleycup2013/2013/05/did-you-see-that-lars-eller-stretchered-off-ice.html\">He suffered a possible concussion and a broken nose</a> – in that order, no doubt, judging by the video. The question is immediately: Was it a legal hit? </p><p>In the clip, the term \"suicide pass\" is mentioned. Indeed it was, and Eller was essentially completely blind to Gryba's incoming. Gryba does appear to get his shoulder high on Eller, whether intentional or not. It was bound to be a brutal hit, just about any way you slice it. The blood after he fell to the ice sealed the major penalty. Does Gryba deserve a hearing with the league?</p><p>Over <a href=\"http://video.tsn.ca/?dl=pipe42/latest/1/0/918384/clip/0\">at TSN former NHL ref Kerry \"the hair\" Fraser evaluates the call</a> and says it was a \"clean hit with a bad result,\" arguing that Gryba's hip was what made contact with Eller. As for the head contact? \"What happened there was that the secondary contact, was, as he passed through and off the centre line, the head of Eller contacted the back shoulder cap of Gryba.\" </p><p>Frankly, I'm still in the camp that believes the principle point of contact is the head, not Eller's mid-section.</p><p>More pressing for Montreal now, though, is how to recover from this loss – of both the game and one of their best players. The Habs looked very sluggish in the third, as if they weren't prepared to play a high-tempo game for a full 60 minutes. Two things they must do right away: First, be more physical. They are simply not going anywhere in the playoffs without that. And second, Montreal has to start getting bodies in front of Anderson, who was phenomenal Thursday night (he stared down 50 shots). Both will be difficult for a team that's not necessarily built for either assignment. </p><p><strong>Update</strong> (Friday, 4pm ET): <a href=\"http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=422306\">Gryba suspended for two games</a>.</p><h2>Don't discount the backup goalie with MS</h2><p>Minnesota was always expected to have a tough time with the Chicago Blackhawks, but literally nobody on this Earth could have predicted that Wild goalie Niklas Backstrom would have been injured so early in Tuesday night's game that the game hadn't even started yet. </p><p>Here's all we know about what happened (hint: not a lot).</p><p><em></em></p><p>In steps backup goalie Josh Harding, a guy who'd only played one playoff game in his life, and who happens to have been diagnosed with Multiple Sclerosis just last year. Not that this last fact necessarily would mean he is any worse at his job – in fact, quite the contrary, as it turned out. Though the Wild ultimately fell to the Blackhawks 2-1, he backstopped them to overtime and made 35 saves along the way. </p><p>Blackhawks forward Patrick Sharp <a href=\"http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Minnesota/2013/05/01/20785911.html\">had this to say about Harding</a>: \"You have to tip your hat to what Josh is going through. It's pretty amazing that he's able to play at the level he does, it's an inspiration for a lot of people.\"</p><p>At the moment, <a href=\"http://espn.go.com/nhl/playoffs/2013/story/_/id/9236727/niklas-backstrom-minnesota-wild-miss-game-2-chicago-blackhawks\">Backstrom is listed day-to-day</a> and is not likely to start Friday, so Harding may get the nod again. Will he be this year's Braden Holtby?</p><h2>The Leafs have obviously not been in the playoffs for a while</h2><p>Perhaps it's unfair to expect the Leafs to be able to take on the Bruins at quite the calibre that's necessary to win a playoff series. After all, this team has virtually no playoff experience. Their captain, Dion Phaneuf does, as does Joffrey Lupul, but really, this is not a team that's very familiar with the pressures of the postseason. The Bruins were shaky down the stretch, but this team has a strong collective memory of winning a Stanley Cup. That showed Wednesday night, as they came together, out-shot (40-20), out-chanced, and straight up out-played the Leafs.</p><p>Over at the National Post, Bruce Arthur breaks it down, noting that Leafs' coach Randy Carlyle is looking to make some changes for Game Two (obviously) but no matter what he does, it might not be enough to overcome what Arthur calls the \"structural demolition\" that was Game One.</p><p>Arthur highlights one man in particular, and it is truly galling.</p><blockquote><p>\"What about matchups? Phil Kessel didn't attempt a shot on goal until the third period and played just 13:51, his second-lowest total of the season. He played just 3:20 in the third period, when the game was out of sight. Of his nearly 12 minutes at even strength, 10 came against Zdeno Chara, and eight came against Patrice Bergeron, two shutdown artists.\" </p></blockquote><p>Carlyle pointed out that being on the road, matchups are tougher. True, but this seems like an extreme. Even if the Leafs were to improve in Game Two (very possible) or Game Three, when they're back in Toronto (even more possible), they would have to rely on the Bruins being worse (much less possible). </p><p>Over at the CBC, Tim Whamsby made note of one thing – perhaps the source of an extra bit of motivation in Boston:</p><blockquote><p>\"A few of the local reporters I talked to remarked afterwards that this was the Bruins best game of the season. The atmosphere in their dressing room was buoyant as players talked about the win next to a Bruins sweater that hung on one wall with Boston 617 Strong stitched on the back, in honour of the victims of the Boston Marathon bombings last month.\"</p></blockquote><h2>Throwing elbows: Andrew Ference gets suspended</h2><p>Speaking of head shots and the Maple Leafs, Toronto fans will probably be happy to hear that Boston defenceman Andrew Ference landed himself a one-game suspension for his elbow on Mikhail Grabovski Wednesday night. In case you missed that hit, here it is:</p><p><em></em></p><p>Yuck. Suspension deserved. Nothing about what Ference is doing down there needed an elbow to be thrown right at Grabovski's head. Brendan Shanahan said as much in his disciplinary video: \"We don't view this check as defensive in nature. Ference is in control of this play, and not merely bracing for contact.\" Translation: This was totally unnecessary. Poor form.</p><h2>The Capitals are legit (maybe)?</h2><p>Either that, or the New York Rangers are just completely not ready for this playoff series. Thursday night, the Rangers let a 1-0 lead at the end of the first completely disappear and dropped Game One of their series against Washington 3-1. </p><p>All of the Caps' goals came in the second, and for anyone (me) doubting Ovechkin's potential, it's worth noting the man to put them back into it was no. 8 (even if it was thanks to a weird rebound off the end boards that Ovie said was \"a lucky bounce\"). The key point, overall, though, was Ovie's goal came on a power play – an area where the Caps happen to be quite dangerous. And the Rangers gave them plenty of chances to prove it, landing in the box six times Thursday night.</p><p>The prettiest goal of the night, however, was the go-ahead Marcus Johansson grabbed with just over five minutes left in the second. Enjoy:</p><p><em></em></p><h2><a href=\"http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=668207\">NHL playoff schedule</a></h2><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/408284508|2013-10-17T10:28:06Z|6cd49c1420f7e352482c66741cc429afdbca6e13 -->",
